{{italic title}} {{Infobox book | name = De Constantia Sapientis | title_orig = | translator = | image = L Annaei Senecae philosophi 1643 page 302 De Constantia Sapientis.png | image_size = 200px | caption = From the 1643 edition, published by Francesco Baba | author = [[Seneca the Younger|Lucius Annaeus Seneca]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[Ancient Rome]] | language = [[Latin]] | series = | subject = Ethics | genre = Philosophy | publisher = | pub_date = AD {{c.|lk=no|55}} | english_pub_date = | pages = | isbn = | oclc = }} '''''De Constantia Sapientis''''' ({{lang-en|On the Firmness of the Wise}}) is a moral [[essay]] written by [[Seneca the Younger]], a [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] [[Stoicism|Stoic]] philosopher, sometime around 55 AD. The work celebrates the imperturbility of the ideal Stoic sage, who with an inner firmness, is strengthened by injury and adversity.
==Date and addressee== The work is addressed to Seneca's friend [[Annaeus Serenus]] and written sometime between 47 and 62.<ref>{{Cite book |author1-first=L. D.|author1-last=Reynolds|author2-first=M. T.|author2-last=Griffin|author3-first=E.|author3-last=Fantham |title=The Oxford Classical Dictionary|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2012 |editor1-first=S|editor1-last=Hornblower|editor2-first=A|editor2-last=Spawforth |editor3-first=E|editor3-last=Eidinow| isbn=0199545561}}</ref>
''De Constantia Sapientis'' is one of a trio of dialogues addressed to Serenus, which also includes ''[[De Tranquillitate Animi]]'' and ''[[De Otio]]''.<ref name="conte">{{Cite book|author=Gian Biagio Conte|translator=J Solodow|title=Latin Literature: A History|publisher= JHU Press|date=4 Nov 1999 |isbn= 0801862531}}</ref> The superior position [[Sage (philosophy)|the sage]] inhabits, of detachment from earthly future events of a detrimental nature, is the unifying theme of the dialogues.<ref name="conte"/> Since Serenus is portrayed as not yet a Stoic in ''De Constantia Sapientis'', it is usually considered the earliest of the three dialogues.<ref name="smithy">{{cite book|last=Scott Smith|first=R.|chapter=De Constantia Sapientis|title=Brill's Companion to Seneca: Philosopher and Dramatist|pages=121–6|editor1-first=Andreas|editor1-last=Heil|editor2-first=Gregor|editor2-last=Damschen|year=2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9004217088}}</ref>
==Content== In ''De Constantia Sapientis'' Seneca argues that [[Stoicism]] is not as harsh as it first appears. Recalling the figure of [[Cato the Younger]] Seneca argues that Cato as a wise person suffered neither injury nor insult. Although Serenus objects to this paradox, Seneca provides further analogies to emphasize the impervious nature of the wise person. In chapter 5 Seneca distinguishes between ''contumelia'' (insults) and ''iniuria'' (injuries). The rest of the treatise through to chapter 19 consists of discussions on the nature of both themes, showing that the wise person is immune from both insults and injuries. Seneca concludes the treatise praising the idea of the wise person while offering practical advice for all of us who are imperfect.<ref name="smithy"/>
